Hey Terra=C2=A0is doing stuff:A proposal by the founder of the troubled Ter=
ra ecosystem to salvage the project was approved, averting a total collapse=
 of one of the most-watched experiments in decentralized finance.=C2=A0Unde=
r Do Kwon=E2=80=99s newly approved structure, the original blockchain will =
be known as Terra Classic, while its native token Luna, which plunged close=
 to zero this month, will be renamed Luna Classic with the ticker LUNC. The=
 new Terra blockchain will start running a coin under the existing Luna nam=
e and ticker, and won=E2=80=99t include the TerraUSD stablecoinTerra=E2=80=
=99s unraveling, which started earlier this month with the implosion of the=
 algorithmic stablecoin Kwon had touted relentlessly, marked one of the big=
gest busts in the crypto industry=E2=80=99s history. While the outcome of W=
ednesday=E2=80=99s vote represents a victory of sorts for Kwon and his supp=
orters, doubts persist about whether Terra can ultimately be revived.=C2=A0=
The process means Terraform Labs is effectively abandoning the stablecoin T=
erraUSD, or UST, which from now on will only trade on the Terra Classic blo=
ckchain. Designed to maintain a 1-to-1 peg to the dollar, it traded at arou=
nd 10 cents on Wednesday.We have talked a few times recently about=C2=A0Ter=
ra, the blockchain ecosystem whose  algorithmic stablecoin blew up earlier =
this month. One model of Terra=C2=A0goes like this:=09Terra is a company. N=
ot really =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s a decentralized finance ecosystem, a =
blockchain, a bunch of independent developers working on diverse projects =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but let=E2=80=99s just pretend for a minute. (In fact there =
is a company-ish thing called Terraform Labs which helps run Terra, and ano=
ther company-ish thing called Luna Foundation Guard that keeps some of Terr=
a=E2=80=99s money, but here I want to conceive of Terra as a whole as sort =
of a distributed company.)=09The Luna token, which powers the Terra blockch=
ain and is the currency of its ecosystem, is the=C2=A0equity=C2=A0of Terra,=
 the stock in the Terra company.=09The TerraUSD stablecoin (or UST), which =
was supposed to always be worth a dollar, and which maintained that peg by =
being exchangeable for $1 worth of Luna at market prices, is the=C2=A0debt=
=C2=A0of Terra. Like bonds of the company, or like deposits of a bank.This =
model has a lot going for it. UST, certainly, looks like debt: You buy a US=
T for a fixed amount ($1), and you expect to get back that fixed amount ($1=
), and while you hold it you earn interest. (For a while, you could get 19.=
5% interest on UST in the Anchor protocol, a part of the Terra ecosystem.) =
It was advertised as a safe investment, a way to participate in the Terra e=
cosystem with a guarantee of getting your money back.Luna, meanwhile, looks=
 like equity. It has no fixed value; it went up as optimism about Terra gre=
w, and went down as Terra imploded. Luna could go to zero if Terra failed, =
or it could go to the moon if Terra became the world=E2=80=99s dominant fin=
ancial system. There was no floor and no cap on Luna=E2=80=99s value (unlik=
e UST, which was floored and capped at $1); it was just worth some fraction=
 of the future value of the Terra ecosystem.There are some implications of =
this model. One implication is that you=C2=A0might think: Wait, if these co=
ins are the debt and equity of a company, aren=E2=80=99t they securities? I=
f they are securities, and they were sold to US investors, aren=E2=80=99t t=
hey required to be registered with the US Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n? If they are securities that were sold broadly to the general public and =
then lost almost all of their value, shouldn=E2=80=99t the SEC investigate?=
 If big US crypto trading firms and venture capitalists were buying huge pi=
les of Luna from Terra=E2=80=99s promoters=C2=A0and dumping them to retail =
buyers on exchanges while also talking up Terra,  making billions of dollar=
s for themselves while they =E2=80=9Ccash[ed] out on the backs of retail,=
=E2=80=9D weren=E2=80=99t those big investors=C2=A0breaking US securities l=
aws? Weren=E2=80=99t they underwriters of an unregistered securities offeri=
ng, and shouldn=E2=80=99t they have to buy those coins back from those reta=
il bagholders at the prices they paid? These seem like good questions! Some=
 of the answers might be =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0Terra is not=
=C2=A0actually=C2=A0a company, and while Luna and UST are=C2=A0like=C2=A0se=
curities it is not obvious that they=C2=A0are=C2=A0securities =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but I think they=E2=80=99re good questions.=C2=A0I will not pursue them =
further here but, you know, something to think about. If you work at the SE=
C for instance.Here I want to talk about a different implication. Like I sa=
id, Terra blew up this month. The price of Luna fell from over $100 in Marc=
h to=C2=A0a tiny fraction of a penny today, and through the workings of UST=
=E2=80=99s algorithmic peg, trillions of near-worthless Luna were issued to=
 UST holders who were trying to get out. Meanwhile UST, which was supposed =
to always be worth a dollar,=C2=A0traded as low as 5 cents.If Terra were a =
company, you might describe this situation as a bankruptcy. And there would=
 be reasonably well-understood procedures for what happens to the debt and =
equity in a bankruptcy:=09If there=E2=80=99s money around, it goes to payin=
g off the debt.=09If there=E2=80=99s not enough money to pay off the debt, =
then the equity is extinguished;=C2=A0all the equity holders get nothing.=
=09If the equity is zeroed and there=E2=80=99s=C2=A0something=C2=A0left ove=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0if there=E2=80=99s some valuable business that can be run =
as a going concern =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the debt holders=C2=A0get it. They g=
et equity in the new, post-bankruptcy entity, to compensate them for not ge=
tting paid back.=09Generally that new entity will need to pay managers, may=
be raise new money, etc., so the old debt holders won=E2=80=99t own 100% of=
 its equity: The managers, new investors, etc., will get some, as an incent=
ive to keep working at this business that is now owned by its creditors.=09=
But in general the old equity holders won=E2=80=99t get much of the new com=
pany, and usually they=E2=80=99ll get none of it.[1] The debt holders will =
have absolute priority over the equity holders; they need to be made whole =
before the equity holders get anything.You could apply that thought process=
 to Terra. Terra went=C2=A0bankrupt, in the sense that its value is not eno=
ugh to support all of the debt claims (TerraUSD) against it. But Terra stil=
l has=C2=A0some value, in the sense that there is a blockchain ecosystem th=
at Terra impresario Do Kwon and other people are trying to keep alive.=C2=
=A0In theory, at least, people used (and could still use) Terra as an ecosy=
stem for building decentralized applications, transferring money, creating =
