s in lots of parts of the world and paid a lot of bribes to win business.=
=C2=A0This has been well-known and much-discussed for a long time. Yesterda=
y Glencore pleaded guilty to various charges in various countries to, you k=
now, pay up for all the bribes.  Bloomberg News reports:Glencore Plc admitt=
ed to bribery and market manipulation and said it will pay about $1.5 billi=
on to settle US, UK and Brazilian probes that have hung over the commoditie=
s giant for years.The settlements will help remove a question mark that has=
 long overshadowed the trader=E2=80=99s business. But the charges and admis=
sions of guilt paint a damning, globe-spanning picture of how far the compa=
ny, founded by U.S. fugitive Marc Rich, has been willing to go in pursuit o=
f profit.=C2=A0Glencore units agreed to plead guilty to a list of charges t=
hat range from bribery and corruption in South America and Africa, to price=
 manipulation in US fuel-oil markets. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a good=
 day for them to finally get this done because it=E2=80=99s been hanging ov=
er them for a while,=E2=80=9D said Ben Davis, a mining analyst at Liberum C=
apital. =E2=80=9CIt at least allows them to start to move forward.=E2=80=9D=
That does seem to be the general reaction to these pleas: Sure yes of cours=
e Glencore paid a bunch of=C2=A0bribes to various government agencies to wi=
n business, but now that it has written a check to the US government, it do=
esn=E2=80=99t have to worry about the bribes anymore, so it=E2=80=99s good =
for business. The stock went up.It is all pretty standard stuff. The bribes=
 were bribes: If you want to do lucrative commodities trades with state-own=
ed enterprises in developing countries, you will need to build personal rel=
ationships with the people in power at those enterprises, and a classic way=
 to do that is by handing them sacks of cash. So Glencore did. From yesterd=
ay=E2=80=99s settlement with the US Commodity Futures Trading Commission:At=
 various times during the Relevant Period and the Charging Period, Glencore=
, by and through its traders and agents, made corrupt payments to employees=
 and agents working at SOEs of Brazil, Cameroon, Nigeria, and Venezuela. Gl=
encore or its affiliates made the corrupt payments in exchange for improper=
 preferential treatment and access to trades with the SOEs. Glencore=E2=80=
=99s conduct was designed to increase Glencore=E2=80=99s profits from certa=
in physical and derivatives trading in oil markets around the world, includ=
ing U.S. physical and derivatives markets. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The corrupt condu=
ct was widespread within Glencore=E2=80=99s oil business, and supervisors w=
ere aware of and at times directly involved in the corruption.To conceal th=
e corruption, the corrupt payments at times were in large amounts of cash, =
and in some instances, corrupt payments also were invoiced through third-pa=
rty companies, with deceptive invoices to Glencore for euphemistic costs or=
 services such as =E2=80=9Cadvance payment,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cmarketing ser=
vices,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccommission.=E2=80=9D Glencore traders and inter=
mediaries at times used coded language such as =E2=80=9Cfilings,=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9Cnewspapers,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cchocolates=E2=80=9D when referrin=
g to the corrupt payments.We talk occasionally around here about  euphemism=
s for bribes. My general view is that the terms in these invoices =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmarketing services,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccommission,=E2=80=9D e=
tc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the good euphemisms; you want to be able to say =E2=
=80=9Cwhat, no, we hired an agent to help us find business, and we paid tha=
t agent a commission, nothing bribe-y about it,=E2=80=9D even if the agent =
helped you find the business by putting the =E2=80=9Ccommission=E2=80=9D in=
 a sack and delivering it to the local Minister of Oil. Whereas the terms i=
n their informal communications =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cnewspapers,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9Cchocolates=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the bad euphemisms; you=
 don=E2=80=99t want to go to trial and have a prosecutor read an email back=
 to you and ask =E2=80=9Cwhen you said =E2=80=98we have to get 5 million ch=
ocolates for the local Oil Minister,=E2=80=99 what sort of chocolates were =
you referring to?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CChocolates=E2=80=9D might sound cool to=
 you, but it looks really bad to a prosecutor. Whereas if you say in an ema=
il =E2=80=9Cwe need to hire a local adviser and pay a $5 million commission=
=E2=80=9D then that sounds defensible! And means =E2=80=9Cbribe=E2=80=9D! T=
he idea is that if you are going to talk about bribes you should try to do =
it without snickering, because then later you can say =E2=80=9Cwhat no thos=
e weren=E2=80=99t bribes they were commissions=E2=80=9D and maybe a jury wi=
ll believe you.Or that=E2=80=99s what I=E2=80=99d normally say, but my hear=
t is not particularly in it with this settlement, because the whole tone he=
re is so matter-of-factly =E2=80=9Csure yes of course Glencore paid bribes=
=E2=80=9D that it=E2=80=99s hard to fault the people running around calling=
 the bribes =E2=80=9Cchocolates.=E2=80=9D They could have just called them =
=E2=80=9Cbribes.=E2=80=9DThe market manipulation is also pretty standard. T=
he general problem of market manipulation is:=09A few things (Treasury bond=
s, large-cap US stocks, big foreign-exchange pairs) trade in deep liquid ma=
rkets where it is pretty easy to know what =E2=80=9Cthe price=E2=80=9D of t=
he thing is at any particular time, and pretty hard for one trade to move t=
hat price too much.=09This is super useful, and you can build all sorts of =
derivatives structures on top of these things because the underlying price =
is easily knowable and robust. Or you can build index products where, for i=
nstance, people just buy stocks =E2=80=9Cat the market price,=E2=80=9D beca=
use that price feels real and knowable.=09It would be nice if lots of other=
 things =E2=80=94=C2=A0oil cargoes, chicken parts, the interbank unsecured =
lending market =E2=80=94=C2=A0were like those things, trading in deep liqui=
d markets with an observable market price. Then you could build derivatives=
