om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Glencore</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Glencore Plc is a big commodity tradin=
g firm that trades lots of commodities in lots of parts of the world and pa=
id a lot of bribes to win business.=C2=A0This has been well-known and much-=
discussed for a long time. Yesterday Glencore pleaded guilty to various cha=
rges in various countries to, you know, pay up for all the bribes. <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27837758.260614/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMjQvZ2xlbmNvcmUtdG8t=
YXBwZWFyLWluLXVzLXVrLWNvdXJ0cy1vdmVyLXJlc29sdXRpb25zLW9mLXByb2Jlcz9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwNTI1MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBb7264072" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg News reports</a>:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Glencore Plc admitted to bribery and market manipul=
ation and said it will pay about $1.5 billion to settle US, UK and Brazilia=
n probes that have hung over the commodities giant for years.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The settlements will help remove a question mark that =
has long overshadowed the trader=E2=80=99s business. But the charges and ad=
missions of guilt paint a damning, globe-spanning picture of how far the co=
mpany, founded by U.S. fugitive Marc Rich, has been willing to go in pursui=
t of profit.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Glencore units agreed to=
 plead guilty to a list of charges that range from bribery and corruption i=
n South America and Africa, to price manipulation in US fuel-oil markets. =
=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a good day =
for them to finally get this done because it=E2=80=99s been hanging over th=
em for a while,=E2=80=9D said Ben Davis, a mining analyst at Liberum Capita=
l. =E2=80=9CIt at least allows them to start to move forward.=E2=80=9D</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That does seem to be the general r=
eaction to these pleas: Sure yes of course Glencore paid a bunch of=C2=A0br=
ibes to various government agencies to win business, but now that it has wr=
itten a check to the US government, it doesn=E2=80=99t have to worry about =
the bribes anymore, so it=E2=80=99s good for business. The stock went up.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is all pretty standard stuff. The bribes =
were bribes: If you want to do lucrative commodities trades with state-owne=
d enterprises in developing countries, you will need to build personal rela=
tionships with the people in power at those enterprises, and a classic way =
to do that is by handing them sacks of cash. So Glencore did. From yesterda=
y=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/278377=
58.260614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODUzN=
C0yMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB99cf7a33" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">settlement with the US C=
ommodity Futures Trading Commission</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">At various times during the Relevant Period and the Charging Peri=
od, Glencore, by and through its traders and agents, made corrupt payments =
to employees and agents working at SOEs of Brazil, Cameroon, Nigeria, and V=
enezuela. Glencore or its affiliates made the corrupt payments in exchange =
for improper preferential treatment and access to trades with the SOEs. Gle=
ncore=E2=80=99s conduct was designed to increase Glencore=E2=80=99s profits=
 from certain physical and derivatives trading in oil markets around the wo=
rld, including U.S. physical and derivatives markets. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The co=
rrupt conduct was widespread within Glencore=E2=80=99s oil business, and su=
pervisors were aware of and at times directly involved in the corruption.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To conceal the corruption, the corrupt payme=
nts at times were in large amounts of cash, and in some instances, corrupt =
payments also were invoiced through third-party companies, with deceptive i=
nvoices to Glencore for euphemistic costs or services such as =E2=80=9Cadva=
nce payment,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cmarketing services,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccom=
mission.=E2=80=9D Glencore traders and intermediaries at times used coded l=
anguage such as =E2=80=9Cfilings,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cnewspapers,=E2=80=9D or=
 =E2=80=9Cchocolates=E2=80=9D when referring to the corrupt payments.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talk occasionally around here ab=
out <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27837758.26061=
4/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMDQvZ=
G9uLXQtY2FsbC1icmliZXMtY2hpY2tlbnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRt=
X21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTI1JnV0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4ac95179" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> euphe=
misms for bribes</a>. My general view is that the terms in these invoices =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmarketing services,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccommission,=
=E2=80=9D etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the good euphemisms; you want to be able =
to say =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, we hired an agent to help us find business, and w=
e paid that agent a commission, nothing bribe-y about it,=E2=80=9D even if =
the agent helped you find the business by putting the =E2=80=9Ccommission=
=E2=80=9D in a sack and delivering it to the local Minister of Oil. Whereas=
 the terms in their informal communications =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cnewspap=
ers,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cchocolates=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the bad euphe=
misms; you don=E2=80=99t want to go to trial and have a prosecutor read an =
email back to you and ask =E2=80=9Cwhen you said =E2=80=98we have to get 5 =
million chocolates for the local Oil Minister,=E2=80=99 what sort of chocol=
ates were you referring to?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CChocolates=E2=80=9D might sou=
nd cool to you, but it looks really bad to a prosecutor. Whereas if you say=
 in an email =E2=80=9Cwe need to hire a local adviser and pay a $5 million =
commission=E2=80=9D then that sounds defensible! And means =E2=80=9Cbribe=
=E2=80=9D! The idea is that if you are going to talk about bribes you shoul=
d try to do it without snickering, because then later you can say =E2=80=9C=
what no those weren=E2=80=99t bribes they were commissions=E2=80=9D and may=
be a jury will believe you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or that=E2=80=
=99s what I=E2=80=99d normally say, but my heart is not particularly in it =
with this settlement, because the whole tone here is so matter-of-factly =
=E2=80=9Csure yes of course Glencore paid bribes=E2=80=9D that it=E2=80=99s=
 hard to fault the people running around calling the bribes =E2=80=9Cchocol=
ates.=E2=80=9D They could have just called them =E2=80=9Cbribes.=E2=80=9D</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The market manipulation is also pretty stand=
ard. The general problem of market manipulation is:</p><ol style=3D"list-st=
yle-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">A few things (Treasury bonds, large-cap US stocks, big fo=
reign-exchange pairs) trade in deep liquid markets where it is pretty easy =
to know what =E2=80=9Cthe price=E2=80=9D of the thing is at any particular =
time, and pretty hard for one trade to move that price too much.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This is super useful, and you can build all =
sorts of derivatives structures on top of these things because the underlyi=
ng price is easily knowable and robust. Or you can build index products whe=
re, for instance, people just buy stocks =E2=80=9Cat the market price,=E2=
=80=9D because that price feels real and knowable.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">It would be nice if lots of other things =E2=80=94=C2=A0oi=
l cargoes, chicken parts, the interbank unsecured lending market =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0were like those things, trading in deep liquid markets with an observ=
able market price. Then you could build derivatives on top of them. You cou=
ld agree to do large trades =E2=80=9Cat the market price,=E2=80=9D or at th=
e market price plus or minus some spread, etc.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Those things do not in fact trade in deep liquid markets=
 with an observable market price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
But you could sort of pretend they do. There=E2=80=99s probably <em>some=C2=
=A0</em>market, which generates=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>price. You can look=
 at that market and say =E2=80=9Cwell the market price is $X,=E2=80=9D and =
then you could price your large trades off that benchmark market price. You=
 could agree to sell someone 10 million pounds of chicken parts at some spr=
ead to the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2783775=
8.260614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMD=
ItMDEvd2FzLWNoaWNrZW4tbGlib3ItbWFuaXB1bGF0ZWQtdG9vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjUyMl9NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIyMDUyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa11cd5f=
d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  Georgia Dock index</a> of chicken prices, or give someone a =
$1 billion loan at a 300-basis-point spread to <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27837758.260614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMzEvbGlib3Itd2FzLW1hZGUtdXAtYW55d2F5P=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB6f69815c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Libor</a>, or buy a cargo of oil from =
someone at the Platts Los Angeles Bunker Benchmark plus $5 per ton.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because the benchmark price comes from a =
market that is relatively small, you can manipulate the benchmark price (by=
 trading or quoting in that market), and it will cost you less than you=E2=
=80=99ll make on your much larger trade that is benchmarked to that price.<=
/li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, again from the CFTC:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the Relevant Period, Platts generall=
y determined the benchmarks for a given day based primarily on bids to purc=
hase, offers to sell, and trades in the relevant product during a defined p=
eriod of time called the =E2=80=9Cwindow=E2=80=9D that Platts-authorized ma=
rket participants reported to Platts, and which Platts then widely reported=
 to subscribers. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Glencore=E2=80=99s phy=
sical trading activities included, among other things, large-quantity trade=
s, sometimes called =E2=80=9Ccargos,=E2=80=9D of fuel oil. =E2=80=A6 Among =
the cargo trades engaged in by Glencore were numerous cargo trades with a M=
exico-based SOE (the =E2=80=9CCargo Trades=E2=80=9D), including those for d=
elivery to and from the Los Angeles market. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">During the Relevant Period, more than approximately 100 Cargo Trades w=
ith the SOE were priced by reference to the Platts Los Angeles Bunker Bench=
mark. The price of the Cargo Trades was determined by the average of the da=
ily benchmark price on specified days (=E2=80=9CCargo Pricing Days=E2=80=9D=
), plus or minus a specified dollar amount negotiated by the parties. ... O=
n Cargo Pricing Days, Glencore=E2=80=99s trading positions generally had si=
gnificant price exposure to the Los Angeles Bunker Benchmark. When the Carg=
o Trades were sales by Glencore to the SOE, Glencore=E2=80=99s Cargo Trade =
position would be more profitable if the average Los Angeles Bunker Benchma=
rk on the Cargo Pricing Days was higher: if the Los Angeles Bunker Benchmar=
k rose, Glencore would sell to the SOE at a higher price. Conversely, when =
the Cargo Trades were purchases by Glencore from the SOE, Glencore=E2=80=99=
s Cargo Trade positions would be more profitable if the average Los Angeles=
 Bunker Benchmark on the Cargo Pricing Days was lower: if the Los Angeles B=
unker Benchmark fell, Glencore would buy from the SOE at a lower price. =E2=
=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the Relevant Period, on hundr=
eds of occasions, Glencore manipulated or attempted to manipulate the Los A=
ngeles Bunker Benchmark ... in order to increase Glencore=E2=80=99s profits=
 (or reduce losses) from its derivatives and physical trades that priced by=
 reference to the benchmark. Such trading conduct was a regular practice at=
 Glencore, and supervisors were aware of and at times directly involved in =
the conduct. ... Typically, in furtherance of the manipulation, Glencore su=
bmitted generally increasing bids or generally decreasing offers to Platts =
during the trading window, which Platts then reported to its subscribers. I=
n addition, Glencore personnel at times conveyed misleadingly incomplete, =
=E2=80=9Ccherrypicked,=E2=80=9D or inaccurate information to Platts outside=
 the window, such as information regarding Glencore personnel=E2=80=99s pur=
ported views of the market conditions or of supply and demand, knowing that=
 such information could and did influence Platts=E2=80=99s assessment.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have agreed to sell=
 40,000 metric tons of fuel oil at a spread to the Platts benchmark, and yo=
u can push up the benchmark by submitting high bids during the trading wind=
ow and maybe buying a few thousand tons of oil at inflated prices, that=E2=
=80=99s a good trade: You lose money on your window trades by paying inflat=
ed prices, but you make money on your cargo trade by receiving the inflated=
 price, and as long as your cargo trades are bigger than the window trades =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0as long as the =E2=80=9Coff-exchange=E2=80=9D market is bigg=
er than the =E2=80=9Con-exchange=E2=80=9D one =E2=80=94=C2=A0you make a pro=
fit overall.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpaddin=
g=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
